. The spokesperson argued that Facebook=E2=80=99s ad platform usually limit=
s the spread of polarizing messages =E2=80=94 messages that reflect the vie=
ws of a minority of the population =E2=80=94 by making them more expensive =
to distribute. This occurs naturally, because News Feed algorithms resist s=
haring items that are likely to drive people away.Andrew Bosworth, who ran =
Facebook's ad platform during the 2016 election, tweeted today (https://twi=
tter.com/boztank/status/968149353712951297) that the platform is now less s=
usceptible to being gamed than it once was. But there's mounting evidence t=
hat during the campaign, polarizing messages did resonate broadly. And for =
Donald Trump, they resonated quite cheaply.


